"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438758","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-22","<p>Mandatory Work Activity is a supportive programme designed to help claimants who need extra support from a short work placement to re-focus their job search activity and gain further experience of work. Unemployed Jobseekers Allowance or Universal Credit claimants are referred for up to 4 weeks work experience and will participate on the placement for up to 30 hours a week.</p><br /><p>The number of referrals and starts is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/pre-work-programme-and-get-britain-working" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/pre-work-programme-and-get-britain-working</a>.</p><br /><p>An impact assessment of Mandatory Work Activity was published in 2012 (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mandatory-work-activity--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mandatory-work-activity--2</a>) which considered referrals to the programme in the period May to July 2012. An evaluation of Mandatory Work Activity also published in 2012 (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/evaluation-of-mandatory-work-activity-rr823" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/evaluation-of-mandatory-work-activity-rr823</a>) which included a telephone survey of participants who had been referred to and started an Mandatory Work Allowance placement.</p><br /><p>The evaluation and impact assessment were conducted in 2012 and does not cover the period of the Official Statistics from May 2011 to August 2015.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","20138 ; 20139 ; 20141","2015-12-22T14:05:34.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438758/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438758/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Help to Work Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's publication, Mandatory Programmes official statistics: May 2011 to August 2015, published on 25 November 2015, how many people who joined the Mandatory Work Activity scheme during this period subsequently completed a work placement in full.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438759","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-22","<p>Mandatory Work Activity is a supportive programme designed to help claimants who need extra support from a short work placement to re-focus their job search activity and gain further experience of work. Unemployed Jobseekers Allowance or Universal Credit claimants are referred for up to 4 weeks work experience and will participate on the placement for up to 30 hours a week.</p><br /><p>The number of referrals and starts is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/pre-work-programme-and-get-britain-working" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/pre-work-programme-and-get-britain-working</a>.</p><br /><p>An impact assessment of Mandatory Work Activity was published in 2012 (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mandatory-work-activity--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/mandatory-work-activity--2</a>) which considered referrals to the programme in the period May to July 2012. An evaluation of Mandatory Work Activity also published in 2012 (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/evaluation-of-mandatory-work-activity-rr823" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/evaluation-of-mandatory-work-activity-rr823</a>) which included a telephone survey of participants who had been referred to and started an Mandatory Work Allowance placement.</p><br /><p>The evaluation and impact assessment were conducted in 2012 and does not cover the period of the Official Statistics from May 2011 to August 2015.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","20138 ; 20139 ; 20140","2015-12-22T14:05:34.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438759/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438759/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Help to Work Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's publication, Mandatory Programmes official statistics: May 2011 to August 2015, published on 25 November 2015, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the difference between the number of people referred to the Mandatory Work Activity scheme and the number of people who subsequently joined the programme during this period.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438760","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-22","<p>The economy and labour market have improved since the introduction of our employment programmes. Long-term unemployment has fallen by 35% since 2010 to 509,000, the lowest level in six years. The support we provide to claimants needs to reflect recent labour market changes and the needs of claimants. That is why there will be an increase in funding and new contracted provision to help people with disability and health conditions and the very long-term unemployed return to and remain in work.</p><p>The Mandatory Work Activity and Community Work Placement contracts come to an end in March 2016. We always intended to review the contracts at this time. We will provide support to the long-term unemployed through a strengthened JobCentre Plus offer for those out of work for 12-24 months, and for anyone still unemployed after 2 years we will refer them to contracted provision for further support.</p><p>This approach builds on our best evidence of what works to support claimants back into work, and gets a good deal for the taxpayer.</p><br />","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-12-22T17:31:47.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438760/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438760/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Help to Work Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons the Government has ended the (a) Mandatory Work Activity scheme and (b) Community Work Placements element of the Help to Work scheme.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438761","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-21","<p>The Department’s expenditure in respect of Mandatory Work Activity in each of the last four financial years is as follows:</p><p>2011-12 £9.2m</p><p>2012-13 £13.7m</p><p>2013-14 £15.0m</p><p>2014-15 £12.8m</p><p /> <p /> <br />","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-12-21T10:57:50.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438761/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438761/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Help to Work Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department spent on the Mandatory Work Activity scheme in each of the last four years.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438762","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-22","<br /><p>The Help to Work scheme contains a number of initiatives and programmes, delivered through Jobcentre Plus and Contracted Employment Provision.</p><p>It is not possible to identify the costs of Help to Work activities separately from the total expenditure in Jobcentre Plus. The relevant data is not held in a form which allows it to be clearly identified and separated from other Jobcentre Plus activities.</p><p>The two elements delivered through Contracted Employment Programmes are Community Work Placements and the Supervised Jobsearch Pilot. Expenditure on Community Work Placements was £1.8m in 2014-15. Expenditure on Supervised Jobsearch Pilot in 2014-15 was £6.3m. This is funded by income from the European Social Fund</p><br />","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-12-22T16:56:41.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438762/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438762/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Help to Work Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department spent on the Help to Work scheme in the 2014-15 financial year; and how much of the budget for that scheme for the 2015-16 financial year has been spent to date.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438763","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-21","<p>Fit for Work is now fully rolled out across Great Britain. All employers and GPs are able to refer employees who are on sick leave for four weeks or more, to get a work-related health assessment and help them return to work sooner.</p><br /><p>The Department does not routinely publish funding allocations. However, Fit for Work has been provided with sufficient funding to meet its demands for 2015/16, this financial year. Outturn spending will be detailed in DWP’s published Annual Report and Accounts. Departmental funding for future years has been settled by HMT.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","20146","2015-12-21T11:59:37.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438763/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438763/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438763/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Fit for Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, in what ways he plans to expand the Fit for Work service.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438764","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-21","<p>At 30th November 66.7 full-time equivalent staff are employed by the Fit for Work Service as case managers in England and Wales and 24.8 in Scotland. It is expected that numbers will increase in line with demand.</p><br /> <br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-12-21T14:00:29.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438764/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438764/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438764/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Fit for Work Programme: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many full-time equivalent staff are employed by the Fit for Work service as case managers; and whether the Government plans to increase this number.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438765","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-21","<p>Fit for Work is delivered by health professionals who have an occupational health qualification; occupational health experience; or are able to demonstrate experience and skills appropriate to working in an occupational health context. Health professionals must be registered with the relevant regulatory and/or professional body on the appropriate part(s) of its registers. Fit for Work has an accredited Specialist in Occupational Medicine to provide clinical supervision of the service and provides appropriate supervision from more experienced professionals from whom they can seek advice.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-12-21T14:04:24.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438765/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438765/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438765/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Fit for Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what qualifications are required of case managers employed by the Fit for Work service.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438766","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-21","<p>Case managers receive comprehensive training relevant to the duties they are required to deliver through the Fit for Work service. Health professionals have supervision from experienced professionals from whom they can seek advice. Fit for Work has in place a clinical governance framework to provide oversight of all aspects of clinical service delivery. Fit for Work also ensures health professionals participate in a programme of continuing professional development.</p><br /><p>Continuous training and development occurs on a one to one basis as part of quality assurance.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-12-21T14:08:56.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438766/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438766/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438766/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Fit for Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what training is provided to case managers employed by the Fit for Work service.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438767","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-21","<p>The contract for Fit for Work is published on the Contracts Finder website and can be accessed at <a href="https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive/contract/1516765/" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive/contract/1516765/</a></p><p>Guidance to the provider addresses the negative impact of sickness absence on individuals, employers and the State with the aim to reduce the length of sickness absence and the chances of falling out of work and on to benefits.</p><p>It specifies that the Return to Work Plan takes into account health related issues, workplace issues and non-health/non-work related issues that do, or could, prevent the employee from returning to work.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","20151","2015-12-21T13:56:23.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438767/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438767/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438767/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Fit for Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what guidance his Department has issued to Fit for Work case managers on carrying out assessments of patients referred to the service.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438768","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-21","<p>The contract for Fit for Work is published on the Contracts Finder website and can be accessed at <a href="https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive/contract/1516765/" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/data/contracts-finder-archive/contract/1516765/</a></p><p>Guidance to the provider addresses the negative impact of sickness absence on individuals, employers and the State with the aim to reduce the length of sickness absence and the chances of falling out of work and on to benefits.</p><p>It specifies that the Return to Work Plan takes into account health related issues, workplace issues and non-health/non-work related issues that do, or could, prevent the employee from returning to work.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","20150","2015-12-21T13:56:23.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438768/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438768/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438768/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Fit for Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what guidance his Department has issued to Fit for Work case managers on the content of Return to Work plans drafted for patients referred to the service.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438769","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-21","<p>Fit for Work is now fully rolled out across Great Britain. All employers and GPs are able to refer employees who are on sick leave for four weeks or more, to get a work-related health assessment and help them return to work sooner.</p><br /><p>The Department does not routinely publish funding allocations. However, Fit for Work has been provided with sufficient funding to meet its demands for 2015/16, this financial year. Outturn spending will be detailed in DWP’s published Annual Report and Accounts. Departmental funding for future years has been settled by HMT.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","20145","2015-12-21T11:59:37.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438769/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438769/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438769/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Fit for Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much funding has been allocated to the Fit for Work service for the current financial year; and whether the Government plans to increase that amount.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438770","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-21","<p>Latest figures show there have been 2,441 GP referrals and 1,301 employer referrals with 1,451 Return to Work Plans agreed.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-12-21T13:49:30.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438770/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438770/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438770/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Fit for Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many referrals have been made by (a) GPs and (b) employers to the Fit for Work service since its launch; and how many such referrals have resulted in a Return to Work plan being agreed with the patient.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438771","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-21","<p>The number and proportion of Return to Work Plans produced by the Fit for Work service that made recommendations to employers which were accepted in full is not readily available and to provide the information requested would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-12-21T13:42:16.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438771/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438771/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438771/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Fit for Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of Return to Work plans produced by the Fit for Work service made recommendations to employers which were accepted in full since the launch of that service.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438772","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-22","<p>An evaluation strategy is in place for Fit for Work. As part of this, a formal process evaluation is being undertaken. The formal evaluation will include feedback from employee users of the service, GPs and employers. Return to work will also be covered. Monthly performance group meetings take place between the Department and the providers in both England/Wales and Scotland together with weekly meetings to discuss management information and performance issues.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","20137 ; 20156","2015-12-22T11:57:07.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438772/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438772/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438772/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Fit for Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of patients referred to the Fit for Work service since its launch have since returned to work.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438773","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-21","<p>The number of calls made to the Fit for Work helpline each month since the launch of the service is :</p><table><tbody><tr><td>December 2014</td><td>54</td></tr><tr><td>January 2015</td><td>198</td></tr><tr><td>February 2015</td><td>316</td></tr><tr><td>March 2015</td><td>364</td></tr><tr><td>April 2015</td><td>331</td></tr><tr><td>May 2015</td><td>408</td></tr><tr><td>June 2015</td><td>501</td></tr><tr><td>July 2015</td><td>602</td></tr><tr><td>August 2015</td><td>653</td></tr><tr><td>September 2015</td><td>852</td></tr><tr><td>October 2015</td><td>965</td></tr><tr><td>November 2015</td><td>1084</td></tr></tbody></table><p><br></p><br /> <br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-12-21T14:24:50.767Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438773/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438773/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438773/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Fit for Work Programme: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many calls have been made to the Fit for Work helpline in each month since its launch.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438774","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-22","<p>An evaluation strategy is in place for Fit for Work. As part of this, a formal process evaluation is being undertaken. The formal evaluation will include feedback from employee users of the service, GPs and employers. Return to work will also be covered. Monthly performance group meetings take place between the Department and the providers in both England/Wales and Scotland together with weekly meetings to discuss management information and performance issues.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","20137 ; 20154","2015-12-22T11:57:07.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438774/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438774/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438774/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Fit for Work Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department has taken to evaluate the performance of the Fit for Work service since its launch.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438775","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>The estimated 80,000 claimants referred to in Question 18554 are not disabled for the purposes of the shared accommodation rate exemption. Above this figure there are some disabled claimants within this category who were identified as having rents above the relevant Local Housing Allowance rate. However as these are exempted from the policy they were not included in the original response.</p><p>Of the estimated 80,000, around 31% have self-declared disabilities which are not exempt from the shared accommodation rate. Of these around 18% are in receipt of disability benefits (DLA/PIP/AA) and around 13% are in receipt of either Housing Benefit or the housing element of Universal Credit and are in work.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-05T12:15:29.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438775/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438775/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438775/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Local Housing Allowance: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 10 December 2015 to Question 18554, on housing benefit: social rented housing, what proportion of the estimated 80,000 claimants referred to in that answer are in receipt of (a) disability and (b) in-work benefits.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","20197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438776","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-22","<p>The information requested is not available.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","20162","2015-12-22T10:05:07.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438776/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438776/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438776/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Winter Fuel Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many automatic payments of partial winter fuel payment have been made in each of the last three years; and how many of those payments have been converted to full payments following an application by the recipient.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","20161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438777","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-22","<p>The information requested is not available.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","20161","2015-12-22T10:05:07.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438777/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438777/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Winter Fuel Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in single occupancy households who qualified for the full winter fuel payment only received a partial payment because they did not apply for the additional payment in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","20162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438778","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>We are clear that the existing low-income measures do not drive the right action to tackle the root causes of child poverty.</p><p>Our proposals in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill introduce new statutory measures of worklessness and educational attainment which the evidence indicates are the biggest factors affecting child poverty now and in the future.</p><p>The Department will also continue to publish low-income statistics as part of the ‘Households Below Average Income’ publication.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-05T12:00:44.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438778/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438778/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438778/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, in what ways the proposed life chances measures in the amendments to the Child Poverty Act 2010 will measure child poverty in households with at least one employed adult.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","20328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438779","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>To be eligible for a Universal Credit (UC) Advance payment, the claimant has to have an underlying entitlement to UC, be in financial need, and be able to afford to repay the Advance. These criteria are contained within the Social Security (Payments on Account of Benefit) Regulations 2013.</p><br /><p>If during the initial work search interview, a work coach identifies a claimant is in financial need, or cannot manage until they receive their first UC payment, they will advise them about advance payments.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","20339","2016-01-05T12:07:28.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438779/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438779/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 8 December 2015 to Question 18747, if he will publish the eligibility criteria for advance universal credit payments.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","20325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438780","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-23","<p>There is no Minimum Income Floor (MIF) in the tax credit system.</p><p>In Universal Credit the MIF is designed to address issues in the current system which enable self-employed claimants to receive full State support while declaring low or zero earnings indefinitely.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-12-23T08:30:59.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438780/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438780/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Self-employed: Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to paragraph 1.123 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, what assessment he has made of the effect of uprating the individual threshold in the minimum income floor for self-employed people on the household income of a tax credit claimant family with two children and one self-employed earner under the age of 25 earning £12,194 over the course of a year.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","20318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438781","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>To be eligible for a Universal Credit (UC) Advance payment, the claimant has to have an underlying entitlement to UC, be in financial need, and be able to afford to repay the Advance. These criteria are contained within the Social Security (Payments on Account of Benefit) Regulations 2013.</p><br /><p>If during the initial work search interview, a work coach identifies a claimant is in financial need, or cannot manage until they receive their first UC payment, they will advise them about advance payments.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","20325","2016-01-05T12:07:28.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438781/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438781/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 8 December 2015 to Question 18747, whether people are made aware of advance Universal Credit payments being made available to them at the initial work search interview.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","20339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438782","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>The existing exemptions that already apply to private rented sector tenants aged less than 35 will be carefully considered prior to implementing the Local Housing Allowance rate for similar tenants living in the social rented sector. Consultation forms a part of the policy development.</p><br /><p>This change will require legislative amendments.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-05T11:55:07.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438782/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/438782/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-15","Local Housing Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 10 December 2015 to Question 18555, whether he is consulting on what exemptions should apply to the cap on housing benefit for single under-35 claimants in social housing; and whether changes to the applications of that cap will be implemented through new regulations.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","20259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437832","Home Office","false","2015-12-23","<p>Allegations of rape or domestic violence are a matter for individual police forces and not recorded in statistics relating to immigration control.</p><p>Information on grants of settlement due to domestic violence after leave to remain granted as a spouse, is given in the link below, table se_04, Immigration Statistics July-September 2015) and are available from the library of the House: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2015/list-of-tables#settlement</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2015-12-23T12:03:30.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437832/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437832/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-14","Visas: Married People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the rate of allegations against a spouse of domestic violence or rape by women who have entered the UK on a spousal visa in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL4534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437833","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-21","<p>The Government has a commitment that nearly every car and van will be zero emission by 2050. Already over 1% of new cars are ultra low emission and we expect uptake to continue to rise over time consistent with this goal. We do not provide interim forecasts or targets as this market is now moving so rapidly. We will spend over £600m 2015-16 and 2020-21 to put the UK on track to meet our ambitious long term target.</p><br />",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-12-21T13:25:28.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437833/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437833/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-12-14","Electric Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what proportion of road vehicles in the UK they expect to be wholly electrically powered by 2030.","false","Biography information for Lord Birt",,"Lord Birt","HL4535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437834","Department for Education","false","2015-12-23","<p>Provisional figures for 2014/15 show that 27.8 per cent of pupils in sponsored academies and 37.5 per cent of pupils in local authority maintained mainstream schools were entered for all components of the English Baccalaureate (EBacc).</p><br /><p>This information is published in the Statistical First Release “Provisional GCSE and equivalent results in England: 2014 to 2015”.[1]</p><p>A list of qualifications which count towards the English Baccalaureate is available on the school performance tables’ website.[2]</p><br /><p>[1] 2014/15 provisional table can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/467605/SFR37_2015_National_Tables.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/467605/SFR37_2015_National_Tables.xlsx</a>. (Years: 2014/15 Table 3a)</p><p>[2] A list of qualifications which count towards the English Baccalaureate can be found at: <a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/performance/secondary_14/English_Baccalaureate_list_of_qualifications_July_2015.xls" target="_blank">http://www.education.gov.uk/schools/performance/secondary_14/English_Baccalaureate_list_of_qualifications_July_2015.xls</a>.</p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2015-12-23T14:29:07.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437834/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437834/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-14","English Baccalaureate","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of pupils take a full EBacc range of subjects in (1) sponsored academies, and (2) maintained schools.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL4536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437835","Department for Education","false","2015-12-23","<p>The percentage of pupils who took a GCSE in a qualifying language or humanities subject in 2013/14 is given below:</p><br /><table><tbody><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td colspan="2"><p>Percentage of pupils taking a qualifying subject in:</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><br></p></td><td><p>Languages</p></td><td><p>Humanities</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sponsored academies</p></td><td><p>38.9</p></td><td><p>54.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>LA maintained mainstream schools</p></td><td><p>49.4</p></td><td><p>64.5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br></p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2015-12-23T14:28:46.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437835/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437835/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-14","GCSE","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of pupils in (1) sponsored academies, and (2) maintained schools, take a GCSE in (a) a qualifying language, and (b) a qualifying humanities subject.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL4537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437836","Department for Education","false","2015-12-23","<p>Value added scores are routinely published for individual schools as part of the department’s performance tables, which include the functionality to filter results by an academy sponsor.</p><br /><p>The department does not publish a summary of value added scores for each academy chain or multi-academy trust. Simple aggregations of performance measures can lead to misleading conclusions about performance within a chain since they will often reflect the type of schools that have entered into the chain relationship.</p><br /><p>Earlier this year, the department published a statistical working paper to consider how these issues may be addressed and invited comments from users. This can be found in the attachment to this answer.</p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2015-12-23T14:40:27.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437836/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437836/answer","HL4538 attachment.pdf","HL4538 attachment.pdf","attachment_to_hl4538 ","attachment_to_hl4538 ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437836/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-14","Academies: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of (1) all multi-academy trusts, and (2) multi-academy trusts with at least five schools, achieve above average value added.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL4538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437837","Department for Education","false","2015-12-23","<p>This is a matter for Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector, Sir Michael Wilshaw. I have asked him to write to you and a copy of his reply will be placed in the libraries of the House.</p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2015-12-23T14:41:53.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437837/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437837/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-14","Schools: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what percentage of sponsored academies that were rated inadequate by Ofsted on conversion remained inadequate at their next inspection, and what percentage of maintained schools that were rated inadequate by Ofsted at their previous inspection, but remained maintained, remained inadequate at their latest inspection.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL4539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437838","Department for Education","false","2015-12-23","<p>Ofsted inspection reports for sponsored academies are readily available, as is information on exam performance.</p><p>Sponsored academies are transforming some of the worst underperforming schools under the guidance of an expert sponsor. Becoming an academy enables us to move quickly to replace poor leadership and governance in these failing schools, giving strong leaders the freedom to make decisions that will drive up standards balanced with tough accountability.</p><p>The latest Ofsted Annual Report (December 2015) stated that: “Sponsor-led academies were initially created to raise attainment in schools with long-standing poor performance, often in very deprived areas. Attainment in these schools has increased over time, with the longest standing academies having the strongest performance.”</p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2015-12-23T14:42:38.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437838/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437838/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-14","Academies: Standards","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what evidence they have, if any, to show that sponsored academies are more successful at improving in terms of Ofsted status, when compared to similar maintained schools.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL4540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437839","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-21","<p>The British Government is a strong supporter of Serbia and Kosovo’s respective EU paths, which are dependent on full normalisation of relations between the two countries. Progress requires full implementation of all agreements reached, including the Brussels Agreement of 19 April 2013, and is managed through the EU facilitated Dialogue. We make regular representations to encourage both governments to fully implement all agreements. Following a successful Dialogue meeting in August, the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), issued a press statement on 26 August urging both Serbia and Kosovo to maintain this positive momentum. The Foreign Secretary also made clear that completing the implementation of all their agreements will be an important step towards normalising relations between the two countries and increasing regional stability and security.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-21T14:42:55.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437839/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437839/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","Serbia: Kosovo","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the governments of Serbia and Kosovo about implementing the agreements already reached in negotiations under EU auspices.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437840","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-30","We continue to monitor specific cases and regularly underline the importance of freedom of expression and all fundamental freedoms as part of our broader dialogue with the Turkish government. Our Ambassador to Turkey highlighted his concerns about the number of journalists detained in Turkey, including Mr Dündar and Mr Gül, in his public blog released on International Human Rights day. We welcomed the EU Commission’s Annual Progress Report on Turkey, released on 10 November, which highlighted the need for further reforms from Turkey in these and other areas. Freedom of expression must be respected and all media outlets must be allowed to report freely without intimidation.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-30T14:12:48.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437840/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437840/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","Turkey: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they last made representations to the government of Turkey about freedom of expression and information, as provided for by the European Convention on Human Rights, and with what result.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437841","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-30","<p>We continue to monitor specific cases and regularly underline the importance of freedom of expression and all fundamental freedoms as part of our broader dialogue with the Turkish government. Our Ambassador to Turkey highlighted his concerns about the number of journalists detained in Turkey, including Mr Dündar and Mr Gül, in his public blog released on International Human Rights day. We welcomed the EU Commission’s Annual Progress Report on Turkey, released on 10 November, which highlighted the need for further reforms from Turkey in these and other areas. Freedom of expression must be respected and all media outlets must be allowed to report freely without intimidation.</p><br />",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-30T14:14:06.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437841/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437841/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","Turkey: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will call for the release or charging of Can Dündar and Erdem Gul of CNN Turk, arrested in connection with alleged offences in May; and whether they are making representations to the government of Turkey about the recent arrests of seven teachers and three others connected with Gülen schools in Manisa province.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437842","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-17","<p>The Kurds will play an important role in a political settlement for Syria. Members of all major communities of Syrian society participated in the Riyadh Opposition Conference. This included minorities such as the Kurds in the major political parties. Opposition representatives agreed to form a “High Negotiating Committee” to negotiate with the Syrian regime, under the auspices of the UN. The International Syria Support Group has agreed that protecting the rights of all Syrians regardless of ethnicity or religious domination is fundamental. The UK will continue to advocate this, as the political discussions continue.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-17T15:46:27.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437842/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437842/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","Syria: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of why representatives of the cantons of Rojava were not invited to the recent conference of Syrian opposition groups in Riyadh, and whether they will call for their inclusion in any future meetings.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437843","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-31","Turkey recognises the role that Syrian Kurds have to play in the fight against Daesh, and accepts that Syrian Kurds receive support from the Global Coalition to Counter Daesh. We have a close dialogue with the Government of Turkey about ensuring humanitarian and other supplies reach the communities of northern Syria.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-31T10:48:19.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437843/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437843/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","Turkey: Syria","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether the government of Turkey has placed a complete or partial embargo on supplies to, and exports from, the cantons of northern Syria; and whether they plan to make any representations to the government of Turkey based on that assessment.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437844","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-21","<p>Meeting the humanitarian needs of the huge numbers of refugees arriving in Greece this year is a major challenge. The UK has so far provided £4.5 million to trusted partners working in Greece in support of the Greek authorities. With our funding, the Red Cross is providing assistance and emergency first aid to refugees and migrants arriving on the beaches. We are also providing assistance through the International Organisation for Migration and UNHCR, who are delivering essential coordination, reception and registration support, direct physical assistance, and protection services for the most vulnerable people. UK support is also being delivered via a consortium of NGOs led by the Start Network, and via the EU’s Civil Protection Mechanism, through which we have provided in-kind assistance of blankets, sleeping bags and tents.</p><p>The scale of the response by aid agencies has been impressive but we continue to push for greater coordination, both between agencies and with the Greek government. We are holding discussions with major agencies and NGOs to assess the best way to do this and to plan effectively for 2016. We remain committed to responding in the most effective and comprehensive manner. DFID officials have also recently travelled to Greece to assess the current situation on the ground and how to further scale up support. We will consider further support as needs emerge.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-12-21T14:37:02.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437844/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437844/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-14","Greek Islands: Humanitarian Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the extent aid agencies, including both UN and voluntary organisations, are working in the Greek islands nearest to Turkey; and whether they plan to encourage those agencies to do further work.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL4546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437845","Department for Education","false","2015-12-21","<p>We are currently considering the conclusions and recommendations of the caste feasibility study as part of our wider consideration of the implications of the <em>Tirkey v Chandok</em> tribunal judgments. As I said in my reply of 1 December, we will keep the House informed of further developments on this matter.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-12-21T14:28:37.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437845/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437845/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-14","Castes: Discrimination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 1 December (HL3647), why they have not yet published the 2014 feasibility study on caste discrimination.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL4547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437846","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-22","<p>We have consistently made clear that prisoner voting is a matter for parliament to determine.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2015-12-22T17:48:15.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437846/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437846/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-14","Prisoners: Voting Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they plan to take in response to the judgment of the Grand Chamber of the European Court of Human Rights in <i>Hirst v The United Kingdom (No. 2) </i>Application 74025/01, and the interim resolution of 9 December of the Committee of Ministers of the Council of Europe expressing "profound concern that the blanket ban on the right of convicted prisoners in custody to vote remains in place."","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL4548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437847","Department of Health","false","2015-12-21","<p>Every unexpected death of a patient in a mental health hospital is a matter of concern. In March 2015 NHS England issued their <em>Serious Incident Framework</em>. This gives guidance on good practice in responding to patient deaths, including those of people detained under the Mental Health Act 1983. This includes guidance on the circumstances in which National Health Service organisations should set up an independent investigation, in addition to the Coroner’s inquest. A copy of the Framework is attached.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-12-21T17:21:51.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437847/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437847/answer","NHS England Serious Incident Framework -March 2015.pdf","NHS England Serious Incident Framework -March 2015.pdf","Serious Incident Framework","Serious Incident Framework","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437847/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","Compulsorily Detained Psychiatric Patients: Death","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will introduce a new independent system for investigating the deaths of persons detained under the Mental Health Act 1983, as requested by the Care Quality Commission.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL4549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437848","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-22","Our UN pledges renew our enduring commitment to promoting universal human rights. This includes work to abolish the death penalty. As I have said repeatedly in this House, this Government opposes the death penalty in all circumstances and we continue to call on all states to abolish it.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-22T14:24:45.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437848/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437848/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","Capital Punishment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether opposition to the death penalty remains a key human rights priority for them, in the light of the UK’s candidacy for the UN Human Rights Council.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL4550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437849","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-08","<p>There has been no assessment. However, the proposals in the Bill are not about party funding. The Trade Union Bill is introducing a greater level of transparency into union activities by requiring union members to make an active decision to contribute to a union’s political fund.</p><br /><p>If union members want a political fund they are perfectly free to contribute to one, so, this will not necessarily lead to a reduction in the funds available.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-01-08T11:05:18.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437849/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437849/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-14","Labour Party: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the estimated annual financial loss to the Labour Party following the implementation of clause 10 in the Trade Union Bill, which will reverse the current opt-out process.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL4551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437850","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-08","<p>Clause 10 of the Trade Union Bill takes forward the Government’s manifesto commitment to introduce a greater level of transparency into union activities by requiring union members to make an active decision to contribute to a union’s political fund.</p><p>Therefore, there has been no further consultation on this.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-01-08T11:05:41.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437850/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437850/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-14","Labour Party: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consultation was carried out on the provisions outlined in clause 10 of the Trade Union Bill.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL4552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437851","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-08","<p>The Government intends to publish the impact assessment for the Trade Union Bill before Lords’ Committee Stage.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-01-08T13:55:59.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437851/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437851/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-14","Labour Party: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether an impact assessment was conducted on the provisions contained in the Trade Union Bill that will change the current opt-out process to an opt-in process.","false","Biography information for Lord Mendelsohn",,"Lord Mendelsohn","HL4553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437852","Department for Education","false","2015-12-30","<p>Incidents of bullying and abuse of children and young people via social media by pupils which resulted in exclusions are reported to the Department. The Department publishes these incidents in its annual exclusions statistics. The latest statistics were published on 30 July 2015 and can be found online at GOV.UK.</p><br /><p>The school census guidance provided to schools and local authorities for the 2015/16 academic year explicitly includes cyber bullying in the bullying exclusion category for the first time.</p><br /><p>Prior to this, the guidance for the bullying category only specifically referenced verbal, physical and homophobic bullying.</p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2015-12-30T14:38:52.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437852/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437852/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-14","Pupils: Bullying","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Nash on 9 December (HL4113), whether instances of bullying and abuse of children and young people via social media networks are reported, recorded and included in those exclusions statistics.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL4554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437853","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-21","<p>We selected this three year transition period specifically so that we could responsibly fulfil commitments to existing financial aid projects and ensure government partners were able to build the capacity needed to meet development needs after our support ends.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-12-21T14:28:59.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437853/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437853/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-14","India: Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the humanitarian impact of cutting aid to India from 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Rana",,"Lord Rana","HL4555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437854","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-21","<p>An exit and sustainability plan has been agreed between DFID and partners for every closing programme. In November 2012, we announced we would end our programme of financial aid grants to India by the end of 2015. That is exactly what we are doing. We set this three year transition period so that we could responsibly fulfil commitments to existing financial grant aid projects – all of which will be completed by end of 2015 – after which we will only provide support in the form of private sector expertise and technical assistance</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-12-21T14:38:20.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437854/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437854/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-14","India: Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the future after 2016 of existing projects currently funded by UK aid in India.","false","Biography information for Lord Rana",,"Lord Rana","HL4556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437855","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-21","<p>In November 2012, the Secretary of State for International Development announced the UK would end our programme of financial aid grants to India by the end of 2015. That is exactly what we are doing. We will responsibly fulfil commitments to existing financial grant aid projects – all of which will be completed by end of 2015 – after which we will only provide support in the form of private sector expertise and technical assistance.</p><br /><p>The post-2015 transition plan was agreed in 2012 following extensive consultation with the Government of India (GoI), and has been reviewed annually with the GoI, including most recently in October 2015.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-12-21T14:23:01.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437855/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437855/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-14","India: Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the government of India regarding the termination of UK aid to India in 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Rana",,"Lord Rana","HL4557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437856","Department for International Development","false","2015-12-21","<p>The UK can be proud of the results that its aid to India continues to achieve. For example, during the five years to 2015, UK aid has ensured that over 3.5 million pregnant women and children under 5 are covered by nutrition programmes in eight low income states; that over 1.3 million people have sustainable access to improved sanitation; and that over 600,000 additional people have access to low carbon energy.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2015-12-21T14:19:55.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437856/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437856/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-12-14","India: Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the efficacy of UK aid to India in 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Rana",,"Lord Rana","HL4558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437857","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-22","<p>We frequently bring up the issue of the lack of building permits issued to Palestinians and the challenges this causes to the Palestinians. Most recently, on 24 November our Deputy Head of Mission in Tel Aviv raised the issue with Israel's Head of Coordination of Government Activities in the Territories.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-22T14:24:31.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437857/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437857/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","Jerusalem: Planning Permission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel about data revealing that seven per cent of Jerusalem building permits go to Palestinian neighbourhoods.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437858","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-22","<p>Although we have not raised Wasim Marouf’s particular case, we remain concerned about Israel’s extensive use of administrative detention and also have concerns about mistreatment of Palestinian detainees. We have raised these concerns with the Israeli authorities on many occasions, including at Foreign Minister, Attorney General and National Security Adviser levels.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-22T14:23:55.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437858/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437858/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel about the treatment of Palestinian prisoners, and in particular of Wasim Marouf at Ofer prison.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437859","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-22","<p>We assess that economic security is vital and that Palestinians see tangible improvements in their daily lives. That is why we are a leading donor to the Palestinian Authority and why the Department for International Development have put such emphasis on strengthening Palestinian institutions and fostering private sector-led, sustainable economic growth in the West Bank. We do not plan to make representations on the specific issue of the stone factories. However, we regularly raise the need to enable development of the Palestinian economy. On 19 November our Ambassador in Tel Aviv discussed the need to create economic sustainability in the West Bank and Gaza with the Israeli Minister for Strategic Affairs, Public Security and Information.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-22T14:23:43.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437859/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437859/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","Israel: Palestinians","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 7 December (HL3871), what assessment they have made of the contribution of economic security to achieving peace between Israel and Palestine, and based on that assessment whether they will now raise this issue with the government of Israel.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437860","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-22","<p>We have not made representations to the Government of Israel on this issue. However, the Government of Israel has confirmed to us that they covered the cost of the medivac. We had also previously understood from contact with the Dawabsheh family that their hospital fees were being met by Israel.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-22T14:23:01.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437860/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437860/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","West Bank: Arson","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel regarding the hospital bills sent to the Palestinian Authority for medical treatment of Ahmad Dawabsha.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437861","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-22","<p>While we have not discussed this specific incident with the Israeli authorities, we remain deeply concerned about restrictions on freedom of movement in the Occupied Palestinian Territories. Our Ambassador in Tel Aviv raised the issue of freedom of movement with Israeli National Security Advisor Cohen on 2 November. Our Consul-General in Jerusalem also raised this issue with the Mayor of Jerusalem on 28 October.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-22T14:23:20.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437861/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437861/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","West Bank: Walls and Fences","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel regarding the IDF Fence that separates nursing ewes from their lambs at Qalqilyah in the West Bank.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437862","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-30","<p>While we have not made representations to the Government of Israel on this specific issue we strongly condemn all acts of violence and all incitement to commit acts of violence. Since the start of the current violence we have spoken regularly to both the Palestinian Authority and the Israeli government, urging them to use their influence to de-escalate the tensions.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-30T14:14:52.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437862/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437862/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","West Bank: Universities","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they are making to the government of Israel regarding the attacks on the University in Tulkarem situated in Area A of the West Bank and their impact on students' access to education.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL4564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437863","Department for Education","false","2015-12-18","<p>As set out in the response to the previous question from the noble Lord, Lord Blunkett (HL3996), the £600 million reduction to the Education Services Grant, announced in the Spending Review and Autumn Statement, should have no direct impact on the provision of child and adolescent mental health services, broader special needs support, or psychological services.</p><br /><p>Support for special educational needs is funded from the core schools budget, which we are protecting in real terms.</p><br /><p>The government has made children and young people’s mental health support a priority and we are investing an additional £1.4 billion in children and young people’s perinatal mental health services over the next five years. Each Clinical Commissioning Group has put in place a local transformation plan for children and young people’s mental health to set out how services will be improved. These have been drawn up in partnership with local authorities, schools and colleges to ensure they cover the full spectrum of interventions, from prevention to support and care for existing or emerging mental health problems, transitions between services, and addressing the needs of the most vulnerable.</p><br /><p>Local authorities have statutory duties to provide services and support for children and young people with SEND, including providing educational psychologist expertise. Local authorities are best placed to judge local priorities and to make local funding decisions, and it is therefore for them, in consultation with local people and having regard to the range of statutory responsibilities placed on them, to determine the exact nature of provision in their areas, including how best to allocate resources and how to fulfil their obligations.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2015-12-18T09:01:51.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437863/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437863/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-14","Education: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Nash on 9 December (HL3996), what assessment is being made of the impact on the provision of child and adolescent mental health services, broader special needs support and psychological services, of reductions announced in the Autumn Statement to the provision for areas of education spending in England that are not ring-fenced.","false","Biography information for Lord Blunkett",,"Lord Blunkett","HL4565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437864","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-04","<p>Each government department is responsible for managing its own records up to the point when such records are transferred to the National Archives. This complies with the Lord Chancellor’s Code of Practice on the management of records issued under section 46 of the Freedom of Information Act 2000.</p><p>The Cabinet Secretary has commissioned two recent reviews of record management practices. The first covered the arrangements for the annual release of departmental papers to the National Archives and was published in November 2014. The second, which was published earlier this month, focuses on the transition from paper-based to electronic record keeping; HM Government has accepted all the recommendations of the review and will begin to implement the actions he recommends through the course of 2016.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-01-04T10:07:38.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437864/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437864/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-14","Government Departments: Archives","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their latest assessment of the arrangements for preserving departmental archives, including the role of the Cabinet Secretary.","false","Biography information for Lord Rodgers of Quarry Bank",,"Lord Rodgers of Quarry Bank","HL4566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437865","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-18","<p>The OBR forecasts that wages will grow over the next few years, though at a slightly lower rate than would have been the case had the apprenticeship levy not been introduced.</p><br /><p>However, we know that apprenticeships have long-run productivity and wage benefits for apprentices and the wider economy, which are not included in the OBR’s modelling. On average, an apprenticeship increases an individual’s earnings by 11-16% within three to five years.[1]</p><br /><p>The medium-term benefits of apprenticeships can therefore outweigh short-term wage pressures. We thus consider the net impact of the apprenticeships levy on the economy to be positive.</p><br /><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/further-education-measuring-the-net-present-value-in-england" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/further-education-measuring-the-net-present-value-in-england</a></p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-01-18T13:53:27.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437865/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437865/answer","Measuring_the_Net_Present_Value_of_Further_Education_in_England.pdf","Measuring_the_Net_Present_Value_of_Further_Education_in_England.pdf","Value of FE in England","Value of FE in England","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437865/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-14","Apprentices: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the likely impact of the apprenticeship levy on wage growth over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL4567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437866","HM Treasury","false","2015-12-23","<p>The Government has asked Jayne-Anne Gadhia, CEO of Virgin Money, to lead a review into the representation of women in senior managerial roles in the financial services industry. One of Jayne-Anne Gadhia’s potential recommendations is to link variable pay for the Executive Team to reaching internal targets set by the organisation on the representation of women at a senior level.</p><br /><p>The government welcomes Jayne-Anne Gadhia’s work to date and will consider the final recommendations when the review reports next year.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2015-12-23T10:30:23.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437866/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437866/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-14","Financial Services: Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the case for financial services executives being paid according to the number of women in senior roles.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL4568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437867","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-12-18","<p>Government is committed to seeing more women on the boards of British companies. We believe that a business led, voluntary approach is the best way to get more women on boards, as set out in Lord Davies of Abersoch’s review 2010 into the subject.This approach is working, with 26.2% representation in the FTSE 100, up from 12.5% in 2011. We will build on this with a new programme of work set out by Lord Davies in his recent 5 year report on progress. Government will therefore not be introducing measures to set quotas for women on boards.</p><br />",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2015-12-18T12:36:51.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437867/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437867/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-14","Directors: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to introduce measures to set quotas for women on boards.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL4569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437868","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-13","<p>The Government is a strong supporter of Small Business Saturday, which was this year held on Saturday December 5. As part of a programme of activity to get behind the event and encourage communities to support their local businesses at a key time in the commercial calendar, the Government worked with Small Business Saturday organisers to hold a flagship market with a diverse range of small companies at HM Treasury. All 21 Government departments were also briefed to raise awareness of the campaign, with many using social media channels to highlight the initiative. In addition, 50 Ministers visited a local business in their area on the day, endorsing the campaign through their own social media channels. We also distributed message packs online to 588 stakeholders to encourage them to reach out to their own memberships and support the day. We are now planning to work with organisers to support Small Business Saturday 2016.</p><br /> <br />",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-01-13T12:55:23.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437868/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437868/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-14","Small Businesses","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what plans they have to promote Small Business Saturday.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL4570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437869","Department for Education","false","2015-12-21","<br /><p>New figures released by the Office for National Statistics show that the gender pay gap in the UK remains the lowest on record.</p><br /><p>I am proud of our achievements, but recognise there is still more we must do. To help eliminate the gender pay gap within a generation, we are requiring larger employers to publish information about their gender pay gaps and bonuses. We are also working with business to support and promote Lord Davies’ target of 33% of women on boards in the FTSE 350 by 2020.</p><br /><p>The government is also introducing new regulations that will require larger employers to publish their gender pay gap information. This will encourage companies to take action and drive change on this important issue</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-12-21T14:39:15.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437869/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437869/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-12-14","Equal Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of why there has not been an improvement in the proportion of female high earners in the UK despite initiatives to reduce the gender pay gap.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL4571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437870","Department of Health","false","2015-12-17","<p>Smoking continues to be the leading cause of premature death and health inequality in England, placing a significant burden on the National Health Service.</p><br /><p>The Department remains dedicated to the delivery of effective and robust tobacco control and has committed to developing a new tobacco control strategy to further reduce the prevalence of smoking, working with NHS England and Public Health England (PHE) to identify interventions that will make the best contributions to achieving this.</p><br /><p>Training material and guidance has been developed to support health professionals deliver effective interventions to pregnant women who smoke.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p>PHE will continue to support local authorities by developing and distributing information and advice for the commissioning of effective smoking cessation services.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2015-12-17T17:20:25.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437870/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437870/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","Smoking","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they intend to reduce smoking within the NHS as part of implementing "the radical upgrade in prevention and public health" called for in NHS England’s Five Year Forward View.","false","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham",,"Lord Young of Cookham","HL4572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437871","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-23","<p>Under the current rates retention scheme, and under the new 100 percent scheme to be introduced by the end of the Parliament, there is, and will continue to be, a measure of redistribution of local tax income. This ensures that those authorities with higher relative spending needs compared to their tax base will receive additional funding through the redistribution mechanism; and means that any comparison of local business rates income and levels of deprivation would be misleading.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2015-12-23T15:29:00.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437871/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437871/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-14","Non-domestic Rates","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, following the Spending Review 2015, they have undertaken any analysis of the relationship between the value of business rates collected by local authorities and the local level of deprivation according to the English Indices of Deprivation.","false","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham",,"Lord Young of Cookham","HL4573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437872","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-11","<p>This is a matter of interpretation for the courts to pronounce upon in the context of a relevant case, and it would not be appropriate for the department to provide a general legal opinion.</p><br />",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-01-11T15:26:56.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437872/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437872/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-14","Universities: Staff","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether non-academic employees of a UK university are considered to be public officers for the purposes of misconduct or malfeasance in public office.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL4574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437873","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-21","<p>Her Majesty's Government has confirmed it will hold a debate in Parliament on the principle of Continuous at Sea Deterrence and our plans for the Successor submarine. A decision on when it will be held will be taken in due course.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2015-12-21T14:43:42.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437873/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437873/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-14","Trident Submarines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend, before the Scottish general election, to table a debate in the House of Commons on the decision to build the Vanguard-class replacement.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL4575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437874","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-18","<p>In 2016, we expect to approve the next stage of the programme to replace the Vanguard Class submarines and to commit to further investment to demonstrate the ability of the submarine enterprise to deliver the programme to time and cost. Long lead materials procurement continues within the on-going Assessment Phase.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL4577","2015-12-18T12:36:16.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437874/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437874/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-14","Nuclear Submarines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, following the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 and the revised time and cost estimates to the Trident programme, when the next major orders will be placed for long lead items and hull fabrication.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL4576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437875","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-12-18","<p>In 2016, we expect to approve the next stage of the programme to replace the Vanguard Class submarines and to commit to further investment to demonstrate the ability of the submarine enterprise to deliver the programme to time and cost. Long lead materials procurement continues within the on-going Assessment Phase.</p>",,"Earl Howe","HL4576","2015-12-18T12:36:16.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437875/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437875/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-12-14","Nuclear Submarines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether there will still be a main gate decision for the Vanguard-class replacements.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL4577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437879","Department of Health","false","2015-12-18","<p>NHS England is currently working with partners across the health system to determine how best to take forward the recommendations in the independent Cancer Taskforce's report, Achieving world-class cancer outcomes: a strategy for England 2015 to 2020, and has appointed Cally Palmer CBE as NHS National Cancer Director to lead on managing implementation. She is currently setting up a new Cancer Transformation Board to lead the roll-out of the recommendations of the new strategy, including on workforce, and a Cancer Advisory Group, chaired by Dr Harpal Kumar, Chief Executive of Cancer Research UK, will oversee and scrutinise their work.</p><br /><p>We announced in September that Health Education England (HEE) is developing a new national training programme for an additional 200 staff to get the skills and expertise to carry out endoscopies by 2018. The content of the next mandate from the Government to HEE is currently being determined.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","19882 ; 19883 ; 19884 ; 19886 ; 19887 ; 19964","2015-12-18T15:13:45.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437879/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437879/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to the Independent Cancer Taskforce's report entitled, Achieving world-class cancer outcomes, a strategy for England 2015 to 2020, published in July 2015, what (a) short-term and (b) long-term steps he plans to take to ensure that there is (i) sufficient capacity and (ii) the optimal skills mix within the cancer workforce.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","19881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437880","Department of Health","false","2015-12-18","<p>NHS England is currently working with partners across the health system to determine how best to take forward the recommendations in the independent Cancer Taskforce's report, Achieving world-class cancer outcomes: a strategy for England 2015 to 2020, and has appointed Cally Palmer CBE as NHS National Cancer Director to lead on managing implementation. She is currently setting up a new Cancer Transformation Board to lead the roll-out of the recommendations of the new strategy, including on workforce, and a Cancer Advisory Group, chaired by Dr Harpal Kumar, Chief Executive of Cancer Research UK, will oversee and scrutinise their work.</p><br /><p>We announced in September that Health Education England (HEE) is developing a new national training programme for an additional 200 staff to get the skills and expertise to carry out endoscopies by 2018. The content of the next mandate from the Government to HEE is currently being determined.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","19881 ; 19883 ; 19884 ; 19886 ; 19887 ; 19964","2015-12-18T15:13:45.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437880/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437880/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with (a) NHS England and (b) Health Education England on recommendation 83 in the Independent Cancer Taskforce's report entitled, Achieving world-class cancer outcomes, a strategy for England 2015 to 2020, published in July 2015, on producing a workforce review by the end of 2016.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","19882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437881","Department of Health","false","2015-12-18","<p>NHS England is currently working with partners across the health system to determine how best to take forward the recommendations in the independent Cancer Taskforce's report, Achieving world-class cancer outcomes: a strategy for England 2015 to 2020, and has appointed Cally Palmer CBE as NHS National Cancer Director to lead on managing implementation. She is currently setting up a new Cancer Transformation Board to lead the roll-out of the recommendations of the new strategy, including on workforce, and a Cancer Advisory Group, chaired by Dr Harpal Kumar, Chief Executive of Cancer Research UK, will oversee and scrutinise their work.</p><br /><p>We announced in September that Health Education England (HEE) is developing a new national training programme for an additional 200 staff to get the skills and expertise to carry out endoscopies by 2018. The content of the next mandate from the Government to HEE is currently being determined.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","19881 ; 19882 ; 19883 ; 19884 ; 19887 ; 19964","2015-12-18T15:13:46.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437881/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437881/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he plans to take to increase the number of (a) clinical nurse specialist, (b) clinical oncology, (c) medical oncology, (d) medical physics and (e) therapy radiography training positions.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","19886"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437882","Department of Health","false","2015-12-18","<br /><p>The extension of direct access to diagnostic tests for primary care is an issue for clinical commissioning groups and local commissioners. Although the Independent Cancer Taskforce report did estimate that some additional diagnostic capacity was needed, it did not consider possible increases in capacity required specifically as a result of increasing general practitioner (GP) direct access to testing.</p><br /><p>The Taskforce’s five-year strategy recommends improvements across the cancer pathway, with the aim of improving survival rates, and we will work with the NHS, charities and patient groups to deliver it. We have already announced funding of up to £300 million a year by 2020 to increase diagnostic capacity to meet the new target that patients will be given a definitive cancer diagnosis, or the all clear, within 28 days of being referred by a GP.</p><br /><p>In addition, the recently updated National Institute for Health and Care Excellence referral guidelines for suspected cancer also recommend GPs refer direct-to-test in a number of different circumstances. The guidance is available at:</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng12" target="_blank">www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng12</a></p><br /> <br />","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-12-18T15:27:49.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437882/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437882/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the level of (a) current imaging capacity within the NHS and (b) imaging capacity required to meet the Independent Cancer Taskforce's recommendation that all GPs have direct access to investigative tests by the end of 2015; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","19885"
