ose who have a newly acquired infection and therefore the data do not present incidence of infection. Areas presented reflect region of diagnosis, not of residence.</p><br /> <br /><p><br></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-12-17T14:50:32.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437893/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437893/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437893/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","Sexually Transmitted Infections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many cases of (a) herpes, (b) chlamydia, (c) HIV, (d) syphilis and (e) gonorrhoea were diagnosed in people of each age group in each constituent region of the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","19901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437894","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-16","<p>Under the Pet Animals Act 1951 local authorities can already apply conditions to individual pet shop licences. This includes, for example, restricting the species that can be sold. The power to apply conditions to an individual licence is in section 1(3) of the 1951 Act and is intended to help secure the welfare requirements set out in that section.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-12-16T13:25:42.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437894/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437894/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437894/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-14","Dogs: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will seek a ban on the sale of puppies from retail outlets; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","19822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437895","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-18","We have not made any estimates of the potential increase in numbers of Syrian refugees arriving in Europe as a result of UK airstrikes. The majority of people who have been displaced in Syria have been fleeing regime and Daesh attacks. Unlike the Assad regime and its allies, who are bombing indiscriminately, Coalition military efforts in both Iraq and Syria are specifically designed to minimise civilian casualties. Targets are selected through rigorous protocol, based on the principles of proportionality, legality and military necessity. As the the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Philip Hammond) confirmed to the House on 16 December we are not aware of any civilian casualties as a result of the RAF airstrikes in Syria.","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-12-18T14:37:17.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437895/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437895/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437895/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what estimate his Department has made of the potential change in numbers of Syrian refugees arriving in Europe as a result of the commencement of UK airstrikes in Syria.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","19772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437896","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-22","<p>Delivery of affordable housing in Scotland is a devolved matter.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-22T12:33:28.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437896/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437896/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437896/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-14","Social Rented Housing: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the effect of Scottish Government policies on the level of new affordable social housing in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","19824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437897","Home Office","false","2015-12-23","<p>The haulage industry is hugely important to UK trade and prosperity and Her Majesty’s Government regularly speaks with haulage industry representatives to listen to their concerns regarding the situation in northern France. The Government is funding improved security measures and port infrastructure to protect the travelling public, including HGV drivers, in the Calais area. This includes the introduction of security fencing around port perimeters and along the port approach roads at Calais port and at the Coquelles Eurotunnel site; and the introduction of new secure zones for UK-bound HGVs at both locations. In addition, the UK and French authorities also work closely to share intelligence to combat illegal migrant activity and organised immigration crime.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-12-23T13:36:23.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437897/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437897/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437897/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-14","Large Goods Vehicle Drivers: Calais","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps the Government is taking to ensure the safety and security of UK HGV drivers from their approach to Calais to entering the UK.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","19771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437898","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-18","<p>The government was elected with a mandate to reform the UK’s human rights framework. We are considering the implications of a Bill of Rights on devolution as we develop our proposals. We will, of course, fully engage with the devolved administrations.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2015-12-18T13:01:12.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437898/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437898/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437898/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-14","Bill of Rights: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what account he has taken of the distinction between reserved and devolved matters in the devolved administrations in his plans for the proposed British Bill of Rights and for consultation on that proposed bill.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","19836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437899","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-12-22","<p>We will consult fully on our proposals for a Bill of Rights and announce further details in due course.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2015-12-22T12:41:57.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437899/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437899/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437899/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-12-14","Bill of Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent progress he has made on his plans for a consultation on the proposed British Bill of Rights.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","19823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437900","Department of Health","false","2015-12-18","<p>In accordance with the terms of reference the Accelerated Access Review is not excluding any particular type or class of medicine, but is creating a framework through which to accelerate access for National Health Service patients to innovative health technologies including biosimilar medicines where appropriate.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","20066","2015-12-18T12:38:49.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437900/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437900/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437900/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","NHS: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 23 November 2015 to Question 16399, whether the Accelerated Access Review team has provided any information on how biosimilar medicines fit into its work stream.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","20017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437901","Department of Health","false","2015-12-18","<p>In accordance with the terms of reference the Accelerated Access Review is not excluding any particular type or class of medicine, but is creating a framework through which to accelerate access for National Health Service patients to innovative health technologies including biosimilar medicines where appropriate.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","20017","2015-12-18T12:38:49.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437901/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437901/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437901/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","NHS: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 23 November 2015 to Question 16399, what discussions he has had with the Accelerated Access Review team on biosimilars medicines; and whether he has been given assurance that the final report will make specific recommendations on their use.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","20066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437902","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-17","<p>In comparing the costs of different electricity technologies in the future, DECC typically use the levelised costs of electricity generation. Levelised costs include capital and operating costs over the lifetime of a plant, as well as DECC estimates of projected fuel and carbon costs.</p><br /><p>The most recent levelised cost estimates are available in the DECC Electricity Generation Costs report, available at:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/269888/131217_Electricity_Generation_costs_report_December_2013_Final.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/269888/131217_Electricity_Generation_costs_report_December_2013_Final.pdf</a></p><br /><p>These include levelised cost estimates for (a) conventional hydro-electric sources and (b) gas fired plants.</p><br /><p>We are currently undertaking a comprehensive review of our evidence on levelised costs of electricity generation.</p><br /><p>The above levelised costs however do not take into account all of the wider positive or negative impacts that a plant may impose on the electricity system. So far, DECC’s electricity modelling has considered these wider whole system impacts through a system wide cost-benefit analysis. DECC is currently undertaking a project, which aims to further DECC’s understanding of the whole system impacts of electricity generation technologies.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-12-17T17:13:00.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437902/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437902/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437902/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-14","Electricity Generation: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what comparative assessment she has made of the cost of generating electricity from existing (a) conventional hydro-electric and (b) gas fired plants.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","19828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437903","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-17","<p>In comparing the costs of different electricity technologies in the future, DECC typically use the levelised costs of electricity generation. Levelised costs include capital and operating costs over the lifetime of a plant, as well as DECC estimates of projected fuel and carbon costs.</p><br /><p>The most recent levelised cost estimates are available in the DECC Electricity Generation Costs report, available at:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/269888/131217_Electricity_Generation_costs_report_December_2013_Final.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/269888/131217_Electricity_Generation_costs_report_December_2013_Final.pdf</a></p><br /><p>For hydro plants, DECC assumes a plant lifetime of 41 years for levelised cost purposes. This is taken from the below Arup report (section 6.8.4):</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/66176/Renewables_Obligation_consultation_-_review_of_generation_costs_and_deployment_potential.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/66176/Renewables_Obligation_consultation_-_review_of_generation_costs_and_deployment_potential.pdf</a>.</p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2015-12-17T17:13:33.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437903/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437903/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437903/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2015-12-14","Hydroelectric Power: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, when calculating grants and tax incentives whether her Department assesses the levelised cost of hydro plant over the expected actual lifespan or the shorter lifespan allowed in the levelised cost calculation when allocating grants and tax incentives.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","19868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437904","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-17","<p>Under the Welfare of Racing Greyhounds Regulations 2010, there is no statutory requirement on any greyhound organisation or individual track to report any figures to Defra. The Regulations have now been in force for five years and Defra is currently undertaking a review of their effectiveness. The review is looking at the requirement on tracks to collect injury statistics and how they are then used; and the traceability of greyhounds after they have left the sport. Defra is currently consulting on the initial findings of the review as well as proposals for further action. Further proposals include agreement by the main industry regulator, the Greyhound Board of Great Britain (GBGB), to begin publishing figures for the numbers of greyhounds injured at GBGB affiliated tracks each year, as well as the number of greyhounds that leave GBGB racing each year.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-12-17T14:51:47.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437904/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437904/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437904/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-14","Greyhounds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what information her Department holds on how many greyhounds were retired from racing on the grounds of injury in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","20014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437905","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-17","<p>Defra does not have data on the numbers of non-target animals caught in traps, including snares.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2015-12-17T17:25:23.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437905/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437905/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437905/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-14","Cats: Trapping","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what information her Department holds on how many cats have been caught in snares on (a) private and (b) public land in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","20012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437906","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-17","<p>We have received several representations enquiring about various aspects of the enforcement of the Animal Welfare Act 2006 over the last 12 months. They include representations on local authority powers under the 2006 Act, local authority resources and the ability of the RSPCA to bring forward prosecutions.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-12-17T12:01:18.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437906/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437906/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437906/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-14","Animal Welfare Act 2006","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what representations she has received in the last 12 months relating to enforcement of the Animal Welfare Act 2006.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","20013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437907","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-12-17","<p>The Department for Communities and Local Government does not issue any guidance on keeping animals in rented accommodation.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-12-17T15:45:40.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437907/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437907/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437907/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-14","Rented Housing: Pets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what advice his Department gives to local authorities, housing associations and other housing providers on permitting or restricting (a) senior citizens and (b) others from keeping animals in rented accommodation.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","20010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437908","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-12-17","<p>The Animal Welfare Act 2006 makes it an offence to cause an animal unnecessary suffering. Anyone found guilty of an offence under the Act can be subject to an unlimited fine and/or six months’ imprisonment.</p><br /><p>It is for the courts to decide on an appropriate penalty based on the individual circumstances of each case. To help magistrates to impose appropriate sentences and penalties they are provided with guidance in the form of the Magistrates’ Courts Sentencing Guidelines issued by the Sentencing Council. The guidelines give examples of offences, aggravating and mitigating factors, as well as the range of suggested sentences and penalties for various types of offences. The sentences currently imposed for such offences are not regularly set towards the upper end of the range. This suggests that courts are not finding their current sentencing powers inadequate.</p><br /><p>Nevertheless, Defra understands the concern that existing levels of punishment may be insufficient in some cases. Overall policy on sentencing is the responsibility of the Ministry of Justice (MoJ) and Defra Ministers have made sure that the MoJ is aware of these concerns.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-12-17T11:39:03.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437908/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437908/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437908/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-14","Animal Welfare: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will review the adequacy of the maximum sentences available to the courts for offences of cruelty to animals under the Animal Welfare Act 2006.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","20011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437909","Department of Health","false","2015-12-17","<p><strong></strong>NHS England has a service level agreement in place with Solutions for Public Health (SPH), a NHS public health unit which forms part of the NHS Arden and Greater East Midlands Commissioning Support Unit.</p><br /><p>NHS England has commissioned SPH to provide impartial clinical evidence reviews. These clinical evidence reviews are undertaken independently in line with an agreed methodology and are a critical component in informing evidence based clinical commissioning policies for directly commissioned specialised services, based on the latest published research.</p><br /><p>However, SPH does not have any subsequent involvement in the development, drafting or consideration of NHS England’s clinical commissioning policies.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-12-17T16:29:24.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437909/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437909/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437909/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","Everolimus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions his Department has had with Solutions for Public Health on developing a draft commissioning policy for everolimus.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","19902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437910","Department of Health","false","2015-12-17","<p>Solutions for Public Health has confirmed that they have not had any discussions with either the European Medicines Agency or US Food and Drug Administration in relation to Everolimus.</p><br /><p>This is outside of the scope of the evidence review methodology commissioned by NHS England and would not be relevant to their role as a provider of stand-alone clinical evidence reviews.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-12-17T16:28:10.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437910/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437910/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437910/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","Everolimus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions Solutions for Public Health has had with the European Medicines Agency and US Food and Drug Administration on developing a draft commissioning policy for everolimus.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","19903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437911","Department of Health","false","2015-12-17","<p><strong></strong></p><br /><p>NHS England is currently developing a clinical commissioning policy statement to cover the use of Everolimus in adults with angiomyolipoma in association with tuberous sclerosis complex, as part of its in-year policy work programme.</p><br /><p>In common with its standard process, NHS England has formed a policy working group and commissioned a clinical evidence review. This is now complete and is informing the development of a draft policy statement. The draft policy statement, along with the evidence review, will be shared and tested with stakeholders prior to formal consideration by NHS England in early 2016. The policy statement will be published in due course.</p><br /><p>In the meantime, NHS England will continue to consider funding this treatment for individual patients in clinically exceptional and/or critically urgent clinical circumstances.</p><br /><p><strong></strong></p><p><strong></strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-12-17T16:17:20.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437911/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437911/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437911/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","Tuberous Sclerosis: Everolimus","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps NHS England is taking to develop an in-year draft commissioning policy for the use of everolimus to treat tuberous sclerosis complex.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","19896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437912","Department of Health","false","2015-12-17","<p><strong></strong>NHS England is unable to comment on the overall budgetary position of Solutions for Public Health (SPH). However, NHS England anticipates spending around £485,000 with SPH for the provision of stand-alone clinical evidence reviews in support of its specialised services clinical commissioning policy work plan in 2015/16.</p><br /><p>Equivalent expenditure with SPH in 2014/15 was £285,000 and £190,000 in 2013/14.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-12-17T16:11:14.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437912/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437912/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","Solutions for Public Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the budget of Solutions for Public Health has been in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","19921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437913","Department of Health","false","2015-12-17","<p>It is the responsibility of NHS England to quality assure the work of Solutions for Public Health (SPM).</p><br /><p>NHS England has a service level agreement in place with SPM and this sets out the terms under which stand-alone clinical evidence reviews are conducted and completed. The agreed methodology is based on best practice within the health sector and the collective experience of experts in public health and clinical effectiveness.</p><br /><p>As additional assurance, draft evidence reviews are tested prior to their completion with members of NHS England’s clinical reference groups, which include clinical and patient experts relevant to the service or speciality concerned from across England. Evidence reviews are also now shared as part of both informal stakeholder testing and formal public consultation alongside the draft clinical commissioning policies that they have informed.</p><p><strong></strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-12-17T16:13:54.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437913/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437913/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437913/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","Solutions for Public Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what mechanisms his Department has for quality assurance of the work of Solutions for Public Health.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","19922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437914","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-18","<p>The formation of a Government of National Accord (GNA) is an important step towards engagement with the Libyan Government on reconciliation initiatives relating to Qadhafi-sponsored terrorism. Once stability returns to Libya and our Embassy re-opens we will urge the Libyan authorities to engage again with UK victims and their legal representatives, including those seeking compensation.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-12-18T14:27:31.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437914/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437914/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437914/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-14","Libya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the UK Minister attending the Summit Conference on the future Governance of Libya in Rome on 12 and 13 December 2015 discussed the matter of compensation for UK victims of IRA Semtex supplied by the Gaddafi Regime with any parties attending the Summit; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","19890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437915","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-17","<p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in Bill on 20th July.</p><p>Ministers have considered impacts with regard to all relevant legal obligations when formulating the welfare policies announced in the Bill.</p><p>The intended impact of these reforms is to incentivise work and ensure work always pays.</p><br />","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-12-17T08:54:39.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437915/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437915/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437915/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-14","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect of reducing the work-related activity group employment and support allowance rate on the number of claimants who move into employment.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","19913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437916","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-12-17","<p>The Government set out its assessment of the impacts of the policies in Bill on 20th July and we will review all reports which relate to the Welfare Reform and Work Bill.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-12-17T10:09:10.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437916/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437916/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-14","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if his Department will issue a response to the report entitled Halving the Gap by Lord Law of Dalton, Baroness Meacher and Baroness Grey-Thompson, published in December 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","20080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437917","Department of Health","false","2015-12-17","<br /><p>Five companies have left the Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme since January 2014 as follows:</p><br /><p>- Derma November 2014;</p><p>- Genus (Thornton &amp; Ross) November 2014;</p><p>- Vifor May 2015;</p><p>- Baxter October 2015; and</p><p>- Martindale October 2015</p><br /><p>The Department estimates the financial effect to be a loss of around £10 million in 2015/16.</p><br /><p>The Department’s consultation on options to amend the statutory scheme to control prices of branded health service medicines closed on 4 December 2015. The consultation was accompanied by an Impact Assessment which can be accessed:</p><br /><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/460011/Annex_C_Statutory_Scheme_2014_IA.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/460011/Annex_C_Statutory_Scheme_2014_IA.pdf</a></p><br /><p>The Department’s analysis in the Impact Assessment concludes that the options would reduce National Health Service spending on drugs without affecting the use of those drugs in the NHS. The consultation sought views, comments and evidence on the potential impacts and operation of the options to revise thestatutory branded prices scheme. The Department is considering the responses received and will respond to the consultation in early 2016.</p><br />","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","19895 ; 19897","2015-12-17T16:19:37.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437917/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437917/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/437917/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-14","Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, which companies have left the voluntary pharmaceutical price regulation scheme in each month since January 2014 to date; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","19894"
